29.	lugal-ŋu₁₀ èn-ŋu₁₀ hé-tar-re ki daŋal-ŋu₁₀-šè hé-em-mi-ib-gi₄-gi₄
#lem: lugal[king]N; en[cvne]N; tar[to cut]V/t; ki[place]N; daŋal[wide]; gi[to turn, return]V/i


@translation labeled en project



@(1)Say to my king, @lab{2}to my mountain goat, fair of limb,
@lab{3}eagle-clawed highland horse, @lab{4}to my date palm growing in
a sacred place, laden with glistening dates, @lab{5}say moreover:
@lab{6/8}Saying (the words of) Abaindasa, ofﬁcer of the armed forces,

@(7)who, (to obtain) his master’s favor,
is a constant delight to his master’s heart:


@(9)Being strong, I want to follow my king,16 @lab{10}having vision, I
want to go in your vanguard, @lab{11}at your command please let me be
your messenger! @lab{12}Even when water is still, I can make water
ﬂow; @lab{13}even when the wind is still, I can winnow grain;
@lab{14}even when the boat is still, I can row! @lab{15}I am a
(trained) scribe—I can inscribe a stele! @lab{16}I can... the orders
of the army. @lab{17}The orders of the assembly ... @lab{18}As if I
were planting a tree in my own woodlot, I kneel in the dirt;
@lab{19}as if someone had managed to tie me to my own chair, my hands
are tied with rope; @lab{20}in my own city, where I used to dress in
ﬁne clothing, I am forced to wear dirty rags; @lab{21}forced to wash
in clods of dirt, there is dirt on my face. @lab{22}A beast devours
cadavers, but then retreats, @lab{23}even after the king of beasts
makes a kill, he slackens his jaw;17 @lab{24}even after the canebrake
is consumed by ﬁre, the pond remains (intact),18 @lab{25}and even Utu,
after consuming (offerings of ) ghee and cheese, still reaches out to
(accept offerings from) a pauper’s table;


@(26)(But now) my life hangs by a thread; please take my hand!
@lab{27}I am a widow’s son; I have no one to show concern for
me. @lab{28}Ah, but me— when will Šulgi, my king, restore me to my
position? @lab{29}May my king show his concern for me and restore me
to my prosperous position!


