@translation labeled en project



@(1)En-me-barage-si, the king, @lab{2}built Iri-nanam, Enlil’s abode. @lab{3}Agga,
son of En-me-barage-si @lab{4}made Tumal resplendent @lab{5}(and) brought
Ninlil into Tumal. @lab{6}Then Tumal was abandoned for the ﬁrst time.


@(7)Mes-Ane-pada built Buršušua, Enlil’s abode. @lab{8}Mes-ki-a@-nuna, son
of Mes-Ane-pada @lab{9}made Tumal resplendent @lab{10}(and) brought Ninlil
into Tumal. @lab{11}Then Tumal was abandoned for the second time.


@(12)Gilgameš built Du-numun-bura, Enlil’s dais. @lab{13}Ur-lugal, son of
Gilgameš, @lab{14}made Tumal resplendent @lab{15}(and) brought Ninlil into
Tumal. @lab{16}Then Tumal was abandoned for the third time.


@(17)Nani built the magniﬁcent garden of Enlil’s temple. @lab{18}Mes-ki-a@nana, son of Nani, @lab{19}made Tumal resplendent @lab{20}(and) brought Ninlil
into Tumal. @lab{21}Then Tumal was abandoned for the fourth time.


@(22)Ur-Namma built the Ekur. @lab{23}Šulgi, son of Ur-Nama, @lab{24}made the
Tumal resplendent @lab{25}(and) brought Ninlill into Tumal. @lab{26}Then Tumal
was abandoned for the ﬁfth time.


@(27)From the years of Amar-Suen @lab{28}until the year Ibbi-Suen, the king,

@(29)chose En-am-gal-ana by extispicy as the high priest of Inana of
Unug (=Ibbi-Suen 4), @lab{30}I brought Ninlil to Tumal.


@(31)Written according to the words of Lu-Inana, chief leatherworker of
Enlil.


@(32 - 33)Išbi-Erra built Ekur-igiŋal, Enlil’s storehouse.

