@(1)Say to Ilak-ni’id, @lab{2}thus says Šamaš-¢Êb:

@(3)The journey is 1 month and 15 days. You should leave at once.^1^

@(4 - 5)There is no reason you should not (be able to) report back to me^2^
in Niqum by the 3rd of the month. @lab{6}I have looked after you and
arranged your way.

@(7)Of the 2 donkeys, their silver: 4 skekels;

@(8)Of the linen belt, it’s silver: 1 shekel;

@(9)The price for your boat: 1 shekel;

@(10)The price for ... is 1 1/3 shekel.

@(11)The water is clear. @lab{12}Your miscellaneous expenses will not be included
among these.

@(13)I have calculated for you, in your presence, the value of 2 talents
of dagaltum wool: @lab{14}The merchandise is (worth)77 1 and 2/3 mana of
silver. Bring it to me in tin! @lab{16}Keep on the lookout for @lab{15}the duši’a,
the nirigi and the nirmuš@ír stones

@(17)Your various payments—its capital—has been taken on your behalf
and recorded on a tablet for you. @lab{18}As of today report back to me.78

@(19)It is urgent!

^1^ Literally: “You, yourself, should leave today” (with ud as the object of the 2nd
sg. hamtu transitive verb hé-bí-DU.
^2^ Literally: “bring me your news.”


