18.	u₄ ba-úš-en kur-ra a si-ga hu-mu-un-na₈-na₈
#lem: ud[day]N; uš[die]; kur[mountain(s)]N; a[water]N; sig[clear]; naŋ[to drink]V/t


@translation labeled en project

@(1)Lugal-nesa@e, son of Zuzu, ummia of Nippur, @lab{2}fashioned Tuni-lusag,
his canine emissary, for Nintinuga. @lab{3}To this end, the dog wags its tail
at its mistress and barks at her:

@(4)“Mistress, who provided sustenance in heaven and earth, steward of
Enlil, @lab{5}sweet breast, satisfying all the lands, bringing abundance,

@(6)scrutinizing the intentions of the wounding asag-demon, the one who
examines the bones, @lab{7}sorting the sinews of life (and) the sinews of
death, the one who makes bandages beautiful, @lab{8}who knows those
diseases exacerbated by wounds and deep afﬂictions, @lab{9}the healing
physician, šimmu priest to the sick, observing the entrails of
mankind,

@(10)My mistress, who fashioned me, @lab{11}my name is Tuni-lusag. @lab{12}After
it (= the disease) had healed, I was so named.

@(13)(But) when ... the throat, the asag-demon ... (my) life. @lab{14}My name is
invoked alongside your name! @lab{15}I seek your strength! @lab{16}I am called
Tuni-lusag!”^1^


@(17)As long as I live may I be regarded (with benevolence). @lab{18}When I
die, may I drink clear water in the netherworld.

^1^ X11 adds: After she healed me (lit: after having been good to me), it is I who
was named thus!


